  "doc_id": "56752",
  "text": "For PrP C if it is involved in copper metabolism then its role may be to modulate a redox signalling process. The superoxide radical can be dismutated by PrP C [CITATION_1] in a manner similar to that of the Superoxide Dismutase (SOD) enzyme, however, more recent reports failed to detect SOD activity for PrP C in vivo [CITATION_2] . The superoxide radical can also cleave PrP C into the repeats in a copper dependent manner [CITATION_3] . Although copper is an essential redox transition element through the Fenton reaction it can promote the generation of reactive oxygen species (ROS). Under conditions of oxidative stress, where ROS levels are elevated, PrP C is cleaved into the octapeptide repeats [CITATION_4] . Although PrP C has a conserved cleavage region at 111/110, fragments of 27-30 KDa species as revealed by Chen et al. [CITATION_5] would indicate that cleavage of PrP C can occur physiologically into the repeat region without cleavage of the conserved cleavage site.",
